# [NEWPARTICIPANT](../wg/newparticipant.html)

## Summary
The NEWPARTICIPANT session at IETF 125 provided an overview of the IETF document lifecycle, the transition from Internet-Drafts to RFCs, and the community-driven governance model. The session focused on the technical requirements for drafting documents, the role of the RFC Production Center (RPC), the Nominating Committee (NomCom) process, and the mechanisms for dispute resolution and community conduct.

## Key Discussion Points

### Internet-Drafts and the RFC Series
Alice Russo and Alexey Melnikov discussed the progression of documents within the IETF, referencing [New Participant Program - Session 3 - Standards Development](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-newparticipant-sessa-new-participant-program-session-3-standards-development-00).

*   **RFCs vs. Internet-Drafts:** RFCs are stable, permanent records, whereas Internet-Drafts (IDs) are "work-in-progress" documents that expire after six months unless updated.
*   **Document Formats:** The IETF has transitioned to a v3 XML source format (RFC XML) to support multiple outputs including HTML, PDF, and plain text. This allows for modern features like SVG diagrams and adaptive page layouts.
*   **Document Status:** RFCs are categorized as Informational, Experimental, Proposed Standard, or Internet Standard. The "Draft Standard" category is no longer used.
*   **Sub-series:** Certain RFCs are also part of sub-series such as Best Current Practice (BCP) or Standards (STD).
*   **Streams:** Documents can originate from four main streams: IETF (most common), IAB, IRTF, and Independent Submission.

### Drafting and Publication Process
Alexey Melnikov detailed the technical requirements for authors, referencing [New Participant Program - Session 2 - Participation in the IETF](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-newparticipant-sessa-new-participant-program-session-2-participation-in-the-ietf-00).

*   **Required Sections:** All drafts must include an Abstract, Introduction, Security Considerations, IANA Considerations, and References (divided into Normative and Informative).
*   **Terminology:** Authors should follow BCP 14 (specifically using uppercase keywords like MUST and SHOULD) and IESG guidance on inclusive language.
*   **Authoring Tools:** Recommendations include using `kramdown-rfc` (a Markdown variant) or RFC XML. Tools like `idnits` are used to validate document structure before submission.
*   **Auth48:** Alice Russo explained the final stage of publication where the RFC Production Center (RPC) edits the document for clarity and grammar. Authors have a final 48-hour window (often longer in practice) to review and approve technical edits before the RFC number is issued.

### The Power of the Community
Harold Alvestrand presented on the governance and social structure of the IETF, referencing [New Participant Program - Session 1 - Introduction to the IETF](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-newparticipant-sessa-new-participant-program-session-1-introduction-to-the-ietf-00).

*   **Individual Participation:** Participants act as individuals, not as representatives of their employers.
*   **NomCom:** The Nominating Committee (NomCom) consists of 10 randomly selected volunteers from the community. It is responsible for selecting leadership positions in the IESG, IAB, and LLC. The process is strictly confidential to ensure integrity.
*   **Code of Conduct:** The community relies on professional behavior, focusing on "discussing ideas, not people." Disruptive behavior can lead to a "smackdown" or removal by a chair.
*   **Ombuds Team:** A dedicated, confidential team is available to handle harassment or unprofessional conduct issues that fall outside the scope of technical debate.

### Appeals Process
Harold Alvestrand outlined the dispute resolution framework:
*   Disagreements with a Working Group (WG) consensus can be appealed.
*   The hierarchy of appeal is: WG Chair -> Area Director (AD) -> IESG -> IAB. 
*   In extreme cases regarding procedural violations, an appeal can be made to the ISOC Board of Trustees.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **RFC Editor Website:** Alice Russo noted that the authoritative site (www.rfc-editor.org) is scheduled for a complete replacement this year to improve searchability and device compatibility.
*   **Submission Suspension:** The usual two-week "blackout" period for draft submissions before a meeting will resume shortly to allow participants to post updates based on meeting discussions.

